ed accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThese twelve essays constitute a groundbreaking volume of new work prepared by leading scholars in the fields of history, anthropology, constitutional law, political science, and sociology, who identify the many facets of what it means to be Métis in Canada today. After the Powley decision in 2003, Métis peoples were no longer conceptually limited to the historical boundaries of the fur trade in Canada. Key ideas explored in this collection include identity, rights, and issues of governance, politics, and economics. The book will be of great interest to scholars in political science and Indigenous studies, the legal community, public administrators, government policy advisors, and people seeking to better understand the Métis past and present. Contributors: Christopher Adams, Gloria Jane Bell, Glen Campbell, Gregg Dahl, Janique Dubois, Tom Flanagan, Liam J. Haggarty, Laura-Lee Kearns, Darren O'Toole, Jeremy Patzer, Ian Peach, Siomonn P. Pulla, Kelly L. Saunders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMétisxEthnic identity. 0aMétisxHistory. 0aMétisxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aMétisxPolitics and government. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  aCanadian History.  aIndigenous Studies.  aPolitical Science.1 aAdams, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBell, Gloria Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Gloria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Glen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahl, Gregg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahl, Gre